n OS event burst semantics. Synthetic mocked event streams may not match real watcher behavior and can falsely pass. No LLM dependency.","test_description":"Run the daemon with a real watched directory, perform a single file write pattern known to emit multiple events (e.g., write/rename or chunked write), capture processing invocations, and assert exactly one completed processing for that file path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This failure only appears with real runtime filesystem lifecycle events (delete/recreate/inode changes) while the process stays alive. Mocking watcher internals can hide re-subscription failures.","test_description":"Start the daemon on a real temp directory, delete the watched directory, recreate it at the same path, then add a new file and assert it is processed without restarting the daemon process.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The main risk is ordering logic across watcher intake metadata, queueing, and scheduler modules. This is a multi-module handoff problem, but can be validated without OS-level stress if test controls file metadata/arrival in a local harness. System tests add confidence but are not the minimum for this specific ordering contract.","test_description":"Run intake + metadata extraction + queue + worker modules together in a local test harness, inject several file arrivals 